y 2008 in collaboration with FAO, is based on a seven-point agenda of process, partnership and policy: insti- tuting targeted interventions, such as school feeding programmes; judging development outcomes through hunger impact; reviving public investment in agriculture; building a national and global coalition; making primary education mandatory; providing relief to poor consumers for staple foods; and rebuilding global food policy, including increasing investment in international research institutes. More details on the Hunger Cam- paign can be found at http://hunger.undprcc.lk/insideap/index.html Targeted Interventions against Hunger: A Case for Preschool and School Feeding Anuradha Rajivan Regional Programme Coordinator, Human Development Report Unit UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo HUNGER BRIEFING PAPER SERIES: NO.1 Published in October 2008 Copyright \u00a9 UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo Human Development Report Unit UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo 23, Independence Avenue, Colombo 7, Sri Lanka. Tel: +94 11 4526400 Fax: +94 11 4526410 rcc@undp.org www.undprcc.lk All rights reserved ISBN: 978-955-1416-27-0 Layout and design by A&D Advertising Cover photo by REUTERS/Cheryl Ravelo The views expressed in this publication are those of the author and do not necessarily represent those of the United Nations, including UNDP, or their Member States. The text and data in this publication may be reproduced as long as the source is cited. C O N T E N T S I. The Context: Nutrition Concerns in Asia 01 II. How Meaningful is the Right to Food? 09 III. From India\u2019s Pioneer State to National Scaling-up: Relevance for Asian Developing Countries 11 IV. Potential and Limitations 18 V. Costs and Financing 21 VI. Overall Messages and Conclusion 23 Notes 25 References 29 Acknowledgements This hunger briefing paper written by Anuradha Rajivan of the Human Development Report Unit, is the first in a series of Hunger Briefing papers, prepared for the UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo (RCC) Asia Pacific Hunger Campaign. The Hunger Campaign, based on a seven point coalition of process, partnership and policy is a collaborative initiative of the UNDP RCC and the Food and Agriculture Organisation of the United Nations Regional Office for Asia and the Pacific (FAO-RAP). This briefing paper discusses the urgent need for targeted interventions, such as school feeding programmes, in combating hunger in the Asia Pacific region. This paper, which is based on earlier research work by the author, benefitted from the discussions and feedback at the UNDP Technical Workshop on MDG Based Planning and Development of a Pro Poor Policy Framework held in Bangkok, Thailand in February 2007. Complementary research support provided by Omar Siddique and statistical support by Niranjan Sarangi and Manoja Wickramarathne of the RCC Human Development Report Unit is gratefully acknowledged. I also wish like to acknowledge the contribution of RCC\u2019s Knowledge Resources Committee members: T. Palanivel, Pramod Kumar, Biplove Choudhary, Paul Steele and Yubaraj Khatiwada for their valuable input in finalizing the manuscript. The editorial support provided by Manisha Mishra and Kirsty Hayes is gratefully acknowledged. Omar Noman Chief of Policies and Programmes UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo 1 TARGETED INTERVENTIONS AGAINST HUNGER : A CASE FOR PRESCHOOL AND SCHOOL FEEDING I H unger and malnutrition1 have been par- ticularly resistant to change in Asia. While Asia\u2019s is an enviable growth story, with steadily declining income poverty in most countries, hunger and malnutrition have proved much harder to combat. Although the recent rise in global food prices is being hotly debated inter- nationally, malnutrition has been a serious pre- existing issue, exacerbated during particularly adverse periods - sudden changes in prices, di- sasters, or conflicts. Malnutrition at both ends of the spectrum is of concern - undernutrition due to a shortage of calories and malnutrition due to rapidly changing lifestyles among the poor and the rich, resulting in excesses or shortages of certain nutrients, including obesity2.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9c3ee9f0-3820-4064-9dba-38003c179dc1": {"__data__": {"id_": "9c3ee9f0-3820-4064-9dba-38003c179dc1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/targeted-interventions-against-hunger-case-preschool-and-school-feeding", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Targeted Interventions against Hunger: A Case for Preschool and School Feeding", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/targeted-interventions-against-hunger-case-preschool-and-school-feeding", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c010fad05c1bb1a8bd603d44a1a776d3a6b73a13037ca222e31c5f7da3e1f3f1"}, "2": {"node_id": "c3532b81-6b15-4fa6-8711-0a7711ff15e7", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/targeted-interventions-against-hunger-case-preschool-and-school-feeding", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d89a907eb9be76fcf4acceafc22952c3f8500e878c5bb925eb27fd3736a833a9"}}, "hash": "5a00b3e924590eed43395c5c40d2ed9fa4e30b5183d51a5a43d906b93705753d", "text": "National policies have tried to respond to the issue in dif- ferent ways. The focus of this paper is on direct feeding schemes for the nutritionally vulnerable as a strategic policy intervention and operation- alising the idea of the right to food. A recent ex- ample of interest is from a developed country like Scotland, which introduced healthy and free school meals in 2007 for all income classes in the first three years of schooling3 in order to build pro-health eating habits. After a discussion of nutrition concerns in Asia, in section II the paper explores the concept of right to food. In section III the experience of a India", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "72ee49f0-8a6a-4d8c-beaf-04969638176a": {"__data__": {"id_": "72ee49f0-8a6a-4d8c-beaf-04969638176a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/targeted-interventions-against-hunger-case-preschool-and-school-feeding", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Targeted Interventions against Hunger: A Case for Preschool and School Feeding", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/targeted-interventions-against-hunger-case-preschool-and-school-feeding", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ee6712128046791bbfffdeed027631f7d4042205c27a6e0886b271b2ac8cd9a4"}, "3": {"node_id": "b6a8ec75-b1f6-4faa-84c6-f2c65bae23ae", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/targeted-interventions-against-hunger-case-preschool-and-school-feeding", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "7091fd80edc22a822cd7a670f9a4f530797ee790060da5f5a06215e5645176a7"}}, "hash": "ac574ced4dadea067628f1f1f52e544251630bc4e5d2cc49cc3275239cbb68d4", "text": "is presented where a scaling-up has taken place to the national level, following a pioneer- ing state in which direct food investments tar- geted at the nutritionally vulnerable groups have come to stay through school and preschool feeding. Section IV examines the potential and limitations of direct food investments and finds that while the potential is enormous, going well beyond hunger, the existence of such schemes does not automatically result in the realization of these benefits. There are some persisting is- sues that continue to need policy attention for the programme to be successful. Section V looks at costs and financing. Finally, section VI cap- tures overall messages and conclusion. The Context: Nutrition Concerns in Asia 2 TARGETED INTERVENTIONS AGAINST HUNGER : A CASE FOR PRESCHOOL AND SCHOOL FEEDING Malnutrition in children contributes to over half of child deaths, globally4. With food deprivation, the debilitating effects of infectious diseases and general neglect are compounded. Over 150 million children under age five in the developing world are underweight for their respective ages, including almost half the children in southern Asia. Malnutrition among children is a pretty good reflection of the condition of the popu- lation as a whole. We see progress in East Asia where the numbers more than halved, declin- ing from 24 to 10 million children malnourished over the period 1990 to 2003. From 1996 to 2005, the share of underweight-for-age children in China was eight percent, Malaysia 11 percent, Thailand 18 percent; though in the Philippines, at 28 percent, it was higher. In South Asia, the share of children below five undernourished is much higher on an average, with Bangladesh at 48 percent, India 47 percent, and Sri Lanka 29 percent. The South Asia figures are comparable with or even worse than some of the poorest countries in the world such as Burkina Faso with 38 percent or Sierra Leone 27 percent (UNDP 2007)5. And even in East Asia, there are continu- ing concerns about internal inequalities. The problem of malnutrition is wider and more persistent than income poverty (Rajivan, A, 2004). Table 1.1 shows that the share of chil- dren under five who are moderately or severely underweight is higher than the share of popu- lation living under a dollar a day in Asia-Pacific. If micronutrient deficiencies, anaemia among women and adolescent girls, and other forms of adult malnutrition are added, the share of popu- lation malnourished is more than 50 percent. Si- multaneous existence of nutritional deprivation among some sections and obesity among others is a modern paradox. With food surpluses global- ly, overflowing supermarket shelves people still cannot take food security for granted. Recent dramatic increases in staple food prices are likely to plunge still more people into hunger. Table 1.1: Nutrition status and poverty in Asia and the Pacific Sub region % of under-fives underweight (moderate & severe) 1996-2005* % of population below US$ 1 a day, 2004** East Asia and Pacific 15 9 South Asia 46 31 * Moderate and severe - below minus two standard deviations from median weight-for-age of reference population; severe - below minus three standard deviations from median weight-for-age of reference population (Source: DHS, MICS, WHO and UNICEF). Data refer to the most recent year available during the period 1996-2005. ** World Bank, 2007 The social and private costs of poor nutrition and health can be enormous. Food addresses basic survival and sustenance - the hunger and health Millennium Development Goals (MDGs). Food combats undernutrition, morbidity, mor- tality, and builds people\u2019s capacity to resist and recover from disease. Investment in nutrition can reduce health care costs and cut down the 3 TARGETED INTERVENTIONS AGAINST HUNGER : A CASE FOR PRESCHOOL AND SCHOOL FEEDING incidence of non-communicable diseases. It re- duces income poverty by promoting produc- tivity; and reducing lethargy and absenteeism from work, as well as household expenditure on curative care. Good nutrition promotes cog- nitive, psycho-social and brain development, and reduces classroom hunger, contributing to educational attainment.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b6a8ec75-b1f6-4faa-84c6-f2c65bae23ae": {"__data__": {"id_": "b6a8ec75-b1f6-4faa-84c6-f2c65bae23ae", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/targeted-interventions-against-hunger-case-preschool-and-school-feeding", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Targeted Interventions against Hunger: A Case for Preschool and School Feeding", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/targeted-interventions-against-hunger-case-preschool-and-school-feeding", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ee6712128046791bbfffdeed027631f7d4042205c27a6e0886b271b2ac8cd9a4"}, "2": {"node_id": "72ee49f0-8a6a-4d8c-beaf-04969638176a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/targeted-interventions-against-hunger-case-preschool-and-school-feeding", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ac574ced4dadea067628f1f1f52e544251630bc4e5d2cc49cc3275239cbb68d4"}}, "hash": "7091fd80edc22a822cd7a670f9a4f530797ee790060da5f5a06215e5645176a7", "text": "Combating hunger and reducing the prevalence of malnutrition are aims common to many national plans.6 Nutri- tio